\begin_body

\begin_layout Chapter
Improvements of the EPCglobal C1 G2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The EPCglobal C1 G2 is the most employed UHF RFID standard.
 It allows only for a single tag acknowledgment per slot, even if the PHY
 layer is able to identify multiple collided tags.
 Recent studies have focus on this problem, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013_orthogonal"

\end_inset

.
 They use the post-preamble proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012_orthogonal_codes"

\end_inset

 with a Multi Input Multi Output (MIMO) receiver to resolve collisions.
 The authors assume that all the recovered tags can be acknowledged in parallel.
 However, this technique is not compatible with the EPCglobal C1 G2 standards
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

, due to the post-preamble.
 Therefore, their proposal requires a new RFID standard.
 Furthermore, acknowledging more than one tag in parallel would cause a
 new problem called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ACK Collision
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 due to the simultaneous reception of multiple Acknowledgment 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ACK
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

commands at the tag side.
 Moreover, this parallel acknowledgment causes Electronic Product Code (EPC)
 collisions at the reader side.
 The EPC packet is much longer than the 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

 packet, so it needs an advanced collision recovery algorithm, which decreases
 the system performance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
To overcome these pitfalls, this chapter proposes a system that is capable
 of acknowledging multiple tags within a single slot, resulting in a significant
 increase in performance.
 The main advantage of this proposal is the compatibility with the existing
 EPCglobal C1 G2 tags and readers.
 Hence, the proposed tags can be identified by conventional readers without
 affecting the performance.
 Furthermore, the existing tags can be read simultaneously with the proposed
 tags by the proposed reader.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter is organized as follows.
 Section 1 presents a brief discussion about the conventional reading process
 using the EPCglobal C1 G2 standard.
 Section 2 describes the proposed new system including the modifications
 of the tags and the reader.
 The performance of the proposed system is analyzed in section 3.
 Finally, section 4 provides the practical measurements and the simulation
 results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
EPCglobal C1 G2 Reading Process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section describes, the conventional reading algorithm of the EPCglobal
 C1 G2 standard.
 The reader initially powers the tags in the reading area with a 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CW"
description "Continuous Wave"

\end_inset

 Continuous Wave (CW).
 At this time, the powered tags are in the ready state waiting for the frame
 length information from the reader.
 Then, the reader broadcasts the frame length and notifies all tags with
 the beginning of a new frame with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command.
 As soon as the tags receive this command, each tag selects a slot from
 the frame by setting its slot counter, and enters the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Arbitrate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state.
 When the tag's slot counter is equal to zero, the tag enters the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Reply
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state and starts back-scattering its 
\begin_inset Formula $16$
\end_inset

 bits Random Number (
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

) as a temporary ID in addition to a 
\begin_inset Formula $18$
\end_inset

 bits pilot and preamble used for synchronization as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tag-response-of"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename psr_preamble_new.emf
	lyxscale 40
	width 50page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Conventional tag response 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Tag-response-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed before, in FSA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha1"

\end_inset

, there are three probabilities for each slot: First, empty slot, where
 no tag has selected this slot to transmit its information in it.
 The reader transmits a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query-Rep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command asking the tags decrement their slot counters.
 Second, successful slot, where only one tag selects this slot to transmit
 its information in it.
 The reader transmits an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ACK
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command including the received 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the acknowledged tag enters the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Acknowledged
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state and replies with its permanent Electronic Product Coder 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

EPC
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 code.
 Third, collided slot, where the reader receives simultaneously multiple
 replies from different tags.
 In this case, there are two possibilities: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Systems have no collision recovery capability: The reader fails to identify
 any 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

, so it queries the next slot by sending another 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query-Rep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command.
 As soon as the collided tags receive the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query-Rep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command, they enter the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Arbitrate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state waiting for the next frame.
 The maximum reading efficiency in such systems is 
\begin_inset Formula $36\%$
\end_inset

, when the working frame length is equal to the remaining number of tags
 in the reading area.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename timing.emf
	lyxscale 40
	width 68page%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example of two tags collided slot according to EPCglobal C1 G2 standard
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Two-tags-collided"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Systems have collision recovery capability: They have the ability to identify
 one 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

 from the collided ones.
 Then, the reader broadcasts an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ACK
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command including the identified 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

.
 The tag, which has the same 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

, replies its 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

EPC
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 code, and mutes itself until the end of the reading process.
 However, the remaining tags forget their 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16s$
\end_inset

 and enter the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Arbitrate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state waiting for the next frame.
 The main drawback of such systems is that the reader can only acknowledge
 one tag from the collided tags in a slot, even if it has the capability
 to identify all the responding 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16s$
\end_inset

.
 To overcome this drawback, backwards compatible extension are proposed
 in the following sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Two-tags-collided"

\end_inset

 presents an example for a collided slot with two collided tags.
 It shows the differences between the conventional systems with and without
 collision recovery capability.
 According to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Two-tags-collided"

\end_inset

, the reader, which has no collision recovery capability, couldn't identify
 any of the two collided 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16s$
\end_inset

.
 However, the reader, which has collision recovery capability, identified
 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16_{1}$
\end_inset

 and acknowledged the corresponding tag.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\series bold
Proposed System Description 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, the description of the proposed tags and readers is presented.
 Afterwards, the performance of the proposed system is compared to conventional
 systems.
 The proposed system has the same hardware of conventional systems.
 The main difference between the proposed system and the conventional one
 is the signal format between the new reader and the new tags.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proposed Tag
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed tags have the ability to act like conventional UHF EPCglobal
 C1 G2 tags, which is the default mode.
 However, they load extra properties, when they are in the ready state and
 receive a new command called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Switch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command from the proposed reader.
 The following part presents the main modifications in the signal format
 of the proposed tag:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the EPCglobal C1 G2 standard 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

, conventional tags reply with two possible preambles with the 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

 packet: The short version with 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 bits preamble and the long version with 
\begin_inset Formula $18$
\end_inset

 bits (
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

 bits zeros as a pilot + 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 bits of the short version).
 The proposed tag's signal format has only the long version, but with a
 new structure.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tag-response-of-proposed"

\end_inset

 presents the new structure of the 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

 packet.
 As shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tag-response-of-proposed"

\end_inset

, the new structure has the identical 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 bits of the long conventional long pilot.
 However, the 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

 bits zeros of the conventional long pilot are divided to two parts.
 The first part with 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 bits zeros used for synchronization and the second part with 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 bits orthogonal pilots used for channel estimation.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Set-of-8"

\end_inset

 shows an example of the orthogonal pilots, which are similar to the orthogonal
 post-preamble used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012_orthogonal_codes"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 orthogonal pilot bits have to be orthogonal to the other pilot bits and
 also to the conventional pattern 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 zero bits).
 This property gives our proposal the advantage to have the conventional
 long version tag reply as a valid tag response in the new system.
 This is in contrast to the proposal by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012_orthogonal_codes"

\end_inset

, where the conventional tags are not compatible with their system.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Proposed_preamble.emf
	lyxscale 20
	width 45page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

