\begin_layout Section
Measurement and Simulation Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename eff_comp_8_colours.emf
	lyxscale 40
	width 65page%
	height 25pheight%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Average FSA reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 for the conventional FSA and different acknowledgment scenarios using 8-orthogo
nal pilots as a function of the normalized frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L/n$
\end_inset

 .
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Reading-efficiency-for"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 The proposed tag's signal modifications are implemented on the Wireless
 Identification Sensing Platform (WISP 5.0) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WISP"

\end_inset

, and the proposed reader modifications are implemented on the Universal
 Software Radio Peripheral (USRP B210) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "USRP"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Proposed-reader-to"

\end_inset

 provides a measurement of the envelop signal for reader to tag (down link)
 communication.
 According to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Proposed-reader-to"

\end_inset

, the reader starts with a normal 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Select
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command to set some conventional tag parameters.
 Then, it broadcasts the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Switch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command to make the existing tags switch to the new mode.
 The conventional tags don't recognize this command, so they ignore it.
 Afterwards, the reader sends the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Query
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 command asking the tags to reply with their 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16s$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Proposed-tag-reply"

\end_inset

 presents the tag reply (up link) communication.
 As shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Proposed-tag-reply"

\end_inset

, the proposed tag reply starts with 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 bits zeros used for synchronization followed by 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 bits (one of the orthogonal pilots in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Set-of-8"

\end_inset

).
 In this example the tag replies with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{18}$
\end_inset

.
 It is followed by the 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 bits preamble.
 Finally, the tag replies with its 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

.
 The system is tested in a mixed network between the conventional and the
 proposed tags.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

 of the conventional and proposed tags were identified successfully.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename mean_reading_time_comp_new.emf
	lyxscale 40
	width 65page%
	height 25pheight%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Comparison between the average reading time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as a function of the number of tags in the reading area 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 for different systems.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Mean-reading-time"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The performance analysis is achieved through Monte Carlo simulations\SpecialChar \@.
 Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Reading-efficiency-for"

\end_inset

 shows a comparison between the reading efficiency of the conventional FSA
 and the different acknowledgment scenarios using the 8 orthogonal pilot
 sequences.
 The first scenario is the fully parallel acknowledgment scenario, which
 is proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013_orthogonal"

\end_inset

.
 This system assumes fully parallel acknowledgment for all recovered tags.
 It results in 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[200]{\%}$
\end_inset

 maximum reading efficiency.
 This means that, two tags, on average, are identified per classical slot.
 However, this method is not compatible with the EPCglobal C1 G2 standard
 and can not be applied in practice, because it produces a collision in
 the tag side.
 The second scenario uses only single acknowledgment system.
 It acknowledges only a single tag and neglect the other tags replies.
 It results in 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[67]{\%}$
\end_inset

 maximum reading efficiency.
 This system does not benefit from the strong collision recovery capability
 of the reader.
 The third one is the proposed pseudo-parallel successful slot.
 This system compromises between the single tag acknowledgment and the fully
 parallel acknowledgment.
 It results in 
\begin_inset Formula $100\%$
\end_inset

 maximum reading efficiency.
 This means that it approaches the theoretical lower reading time limit
 of the EPCglobal C1 G2 standard 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Mean-reading-time"

\end_inset

 shows the average reading time of the proposed system compared to the conventio
nal FSA and other recent EPCglobal C1 G2 compatible systems using collision
 recovery techniques.
 According to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Mean-reading-time"

\end_inset

, the average reading time of the proposed system is decreased compared
 to the conventional FSA by 
\begin_inset Formula $60\%$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2010_Trans_CR"

\end_inset

, the authors proposed a collision recovery system that is able to recover
 up to two collided tags.
 Accordingly, the average reading time of the proposed system is lower than
 the reading time of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2010_Trans_CR"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013_multiple_ACK"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $50\%$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $35\%$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Finally, the proposed system approaches the theoretical limit of the EPCglobal
 C1 G2 standard 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

